Ok guys, yes I know it's not scientifically possible to get 200 IBU in
to solution, but this is the result of the calculation from promash
for the amount of hops added in the brew (I could dig out the hop
quantiy, but IBU's is easy).

This was a brew based on the Durden Park beer circles book "Old
British Beers And How To Make Them" - these guys know what they are
talking about.  The recipe in question is the "Whitbread 1864 India
Export Ale", taken from the brewing journals of Whitbread for their
IPA of 1864 nonetheless.  The minimum recommended aging time for this
beer is 1 year.  This beer is so bitter it's undrinkable at the
moment.  I've had a few commercial beers that have been put out way
too early and all I can taste is bitterness - absolutely foul.

Given enough time supposedly this changes in to awesome flavours.  I'm
sure most of you know this, but this is what a true IPA is - they had
to be massively hopped (as well as very highly attenuated and high in
alcohol) to fight infection in a hot, damp environment - namely the
hold of a ship which crossed the equator twice and some of the most
treacherous seas on the planet on it's 3-6 month journey to the Indian
sub-continent from London.  By the time it'b been off-loaded, sold and
distributed, it could well have been 9-12 months before it was being
tapped.

Regards,
Mark
