With the massive amount of hops, high alcohol, and high attenuation
necessary for it to survive the shipping conditions, long aging would be
necessary for the hops and alcohol to mellow out.  Fortunately the long
sea voyage took care of that part.  Since we no longer have to stick our
IPA's in the hot hold of a ship for many months, we can cut the hops
back and age for a shorter period of time to get the same results.

That said, there is still something to be said for massive hopping.
This past fall I brewed a Pliny the Elder clone.  Promash said it was
280 IBU.  You really can't hop past a taste threshold of around 100 IBU
for bitterness.  However, for this beer at least, the extra hops
contributed to an intense complexity and richness to the hop flavor.
This beer uses some 18 ounces of 5 or 6 varieties of hops.  You wouldn't
get this type of flavor out of a single variety of hops.

