I'd rack it to your final serving keg before the 6 month storage.  There
will still be plenty of yeast left in suspension to take care of aging, but
you'll get it off of the majority of the trub/slurry.  I'd also recommend
carbonating it before aging as well since corny kegs are designed to seal
under pressure.  Storing beer long term in an unpressurized corny is probably
asking for some trouble, the lid is most likely not going to be air tight.

Regarding temps, ideally you'd want a cellar temp.  The freezer is OK, but
aging will occur more slowly at lower temps, especially near 36F.  Do you
really get temp swings between freezing and 80F in your house, or by ambient
did you mean you were thinking of storing it outdoors?

Personally, I store my kegs in the basement at ambient temps (which is usually
somewhere in the high 60s F).

John.
