A reply to a few of the responses (I am the OP btw);

There is more extracted from hops added at 60-90 minutes than *just*
bitterness.  IPA is all about the hop flavour from a large addition
changing into wonderful hop *flavours* after a significant period of
aging.

Reducing the hopping rate will mean that a shorter time to mature is
possible, but I guarantee you won't have the same beer.

Now regarding ambient temps etc.

I do indeed live in the UK. Ambient is probably somewhere around
15-16C on average in the UK (60F).  My brewery is in a brick built
'outhouse' - formerly an outside toilet and coal shed that I've
knocked through in to one building (yes, I removed the toilet!  I put
drains in to the floor too).  The ambient temperature of this building
seems to be a couple of degrees lower than outside, especially if I
keep the floor wet - which is normally the case, so probably not far
off traditional cellar temps.

My other choice is to put the kegs in to my lagering chest freezer,
but that sounds like it's not a good idea, at least at this early
stage.

I'm thinking that I'll rack the beer off its yeast/trub this weekend
(it's been in secondary for 3 weeks now) and add a few psi to seal the
keg, and just leave the cornies sitting around the 'brewery'.

Cheers,
Mark
