I definitely agree with you that "over" hopping (for lack of a better
description) an IPA and letting it age in order to mellow to the right
level will be a different beer than one you design from the beginning to
be ready early.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; I'm thinking that I'll rack the beer off its yeast/trub this weekend
&gt; (it's been in secondary for 3 weeks now) and add a few psi to seal the
&gt; keg, and just leave the cornies sitting around the 'brewery'.
">

That's what I'd do as well.  Sounds like the ambient temps in the 'brewery'
should be fine.  However, I'd fully carbonate the beer first rather than
just add a few PSI.  Only hitting it with a quick initial burst of CO2
will pressurize the headspace enough to seat the lid, but over time that
little bit of CO2 will absorb into the beer and the pressure in the
headspace will drop back down to almost 0.  If it were me, I'd go through
a normal carbonation routine so that the keg is at equilibrium at your
intended pressure.  That way the lid will stay sealed during storage.

It won't hurt anything to age the beer while it is carbonated.  As far
as I know it doesn't have any impact on the aging/maturation process.

John.
